Ambush in the Night<br>
Hoa Nam, Viet Nam<br>
1900-0500 Hours, August 21st, 1967<br><br>
The night of the 21st my gun team went out with first squad on a night ambush at Hoa Nam at our old tropical jungle position. Even with, the secured feeling of knowing that the rest of the platoon was close by at Liberty Bridge there was something eerily and fearful about returning to our old position with only a squad. <br>
All the bunkers had been torn down by the Seabees with their heavy equipment. They had used a large caterpillar to plow under the bunkers, the trees and the heavy underbrush.  The sand bags, wooden crates and barbed wire. Hundreds of hours of our labor had all been plowed under in a manner of minutes. <br><br>
Once we set near what had been our position, the night became very silent.<br>
After awhile, we could hear the sound of human voices in the distant darkness.  At first we weren't sure if they were coming from the Marines behind us at Liberty bridge or from the tree line directly in front of us. <br>
Once things quieted down the surrounding trees took on their old sinister shapes and the hard pressed roadway to our right front reflected the full moon's eerily glow, I hated nights like this.  <br>
Adding to the fear and anxiety was knowing that this time that there was no concertina wire out in front of us. No grenades or claymore mines were set up and there were no other Marines standing watch close by.  <br>
This time Charlie could very well be perfectly concealed in the shadows, moving in closer or waiting to ambush our position. <br>
In front of us, the voices grew closer, there were many of them, too many. A deep sense of solitude enveloped the squad and we all set silent, afraid to whisper or to take in a breath. <br>
All night long sweat poured out, and we feared that Charlie would smell our fear. Long, heavy drops of perspiration oozed out of our foreheads, burning the corners of our eyes with a salty embrace. We didn't dare move to wipe the sweat away for fear that the movement might be detected. <br>
We just sat there motionless listening to the whispering Vietnamese voices, echoing in the bushes and moving hurriedly in the heavy jungle, just a short distance away. <br>
All night long, we heard them and heard the water splashing back and forth in their half empty canteens, swishing, clicking and clanking, shuffling and shoving, laughing and other stronger words spoken to hush them and to warn them to be silent. All night, they stayed their distance and we stayed where we were.  We didn't see each other but we heard them and at times they must have heard us. <br>
We smelled them and they may have smelled us because all of a sudden there would be moments of silence, a low whistle would be heard and the drumes would be silent and they would all stand perfectly still and the silence of the night carried a horror of darkness, a deep fear of war, death and destruction and those were the longest. <br>
Then the voices would start up again and all that night, they talked and walked and moved, shuffled and laughed in front of us and they didn't know where we were or that we were out there and they didn't know we were scared.<br>
 <br>
With the morning came a new sunrise and we all lived another day, all because the gooks hadn't wondered into our ambush and because we hadn't ventured out to find them in the night. They went off that day to do what enemy gooks do during the day and we went back to the bridge to do what we did all day long and because neither of us moved closer to the other during the night, and because a few yards of distance and the silence and the fear kept us apart we all lived another day.  <br>

